		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2023"></a><br><code>sle2023/paper01</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2023</a> paper:</span><br><i>Exceptions all Over the Shop: Modular, Customizable, Language-Independent Exception Handling Layer</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/WalterCazzola.html">Walter Cazzola</a>, <a href="../profile/LucaFavalli.html">Luca Favalli</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3623476.3623513">10.1145/3623476.3623513</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The paper proposes a modular, language-independent exception-handling layer that can be plugged into different language implementations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Exception handling is defined as a reusable semantic layer that affects program execution behavior at runtime.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is motivated and validated through a language evolution scenario extending existing languages with new exception features.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
